# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1980-winter-paralympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The **9th Annual International Stoke Mandeville Games**, retroactively designated as the **1960 Summer Paralympics**, were the first international Paralympic Games, following on from the Stoke Mandeville Games of 1948 and 1952.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] They were organised under the aegis of the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The term "Paralympic Games" was approved by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) first in 1984, while the International Paralympic Committee (IPC) was formed in 1989.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The Games were held in Rome, Italy from September 18 to 25, 1960, with the 1960 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The only disability included in these Paralympics was spinal cord injury.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] There were 400 athletes from 23 countries.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] Ludwig Guttmann, the founder of the Stoke Mandeville Games along with Antonio Maglio, head of the Spinal Centre in Rome organised the event which was the first Stoke Mandeville Games to be held outside the UK.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The top 10 NPCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1960-summer-paralympics] The number in parentheses indicates the number of participants from each NPC.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The **1964 Summer Paralympics** (Japanese: 1964年夏季パラリンピック, Hepburn: *1964-Nen Kaki Pararinpikku*), originally known as the **13th International Stoke Mandeville Games**, were the second Paralympic Games to be held.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] They were held in Tokyo, Japan, and were the last Summer Paralympics to take place in the same city as the Summer Olympics until the 1988 Summer Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The Summer Paralympics, so far the only Paralympics held in Tokyo to take place with Spectators, as the 2020 Summer Paralympics in Tokyo held without spectators due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] In contrast with the 1960 Games, many events had more than three participants, meaning that athletes were no longer guaranteed a medal upon completing their event.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Tokyo hosted the Summer Paralympic Games again in 2020.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Nine sports were competed at the 1964 games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] In athletics, a wheelchair racing event in the form of a 60 m dash was added; previously the athletics program had included only field events.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Wheelchair racing has since become one of the most prominent Paralympic events.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The physical medals themselves were created by a team of patients led by engineering instructor George Butler.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The medals awarded displayed an engraving of a globe on one side paired with an image of the sport awarded on the other.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Due to the fact that this was the first time the games were called the Paralympics, the words written on the medals said "Stoke Mandeville International Games – Tokyo 1964." The medals were also engraved and coated by George Butler himself.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Athletes from 17 of the 19 National Paralympic Committees (NPCs) won at least one medal.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given and they are listed alphabetically by IPC country code.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] With a few exceptions, each event contributed one medal of each type to the table (although for team events, multiple physical medals were actually awarded).
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Two bronze medals were awarded in the dartchery, snooker and table tennis events.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Some swimming events did not award silver or bronze medals.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] At the start of the Paralympic Games there was no precision in reporting the results of the competitions.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] However, as can be seen from a 1968 Israeli newspaper reporting an interview with the athlete, she was the same athlete who had won medals in swimming and table tennis in Tokyo 1964.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Athletes with outstanding performances included Margaret Harriman of Rhodesia who won two gold medals in archery, and Serge Bec of France who won two individuals gold medals, one team gold medal and one team silver medal.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Dick Thompson of the United Kingdom won two individual golds, one silver and one bronze in athletics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The United States' Ron Stein won six golds and South Africa's Daniel Erasmus won two golds and two silvers in athletics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Nineteen delegations participated in the Tokyo Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The 1964 Games marked Austria, Fiji, Japan and South Africa's Paralympic Games début.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] South Africa had just been banned from taking part in the 1964 Summer Olympic Games, due to its policy of apartheid.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] It was not, however, banned from the Paralympics until 1980 Summer Paralympics, as Japan (in a host country position) did not oppose its participation.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] A letter from archery medalist Irene Preslipski published in the *Times Leader* on December 1, 1964, also mentions delegations from Ceylon, Mexico and the Philippines marching in the opening ceremony.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] However, these countries only sent in officials.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The Opening ceremony was organized in the Yoyogi Park, and the Closing Ceremony at Yoyogi National Gymnasium.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] About 5000 spectators were present at both of the ceremonies.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Then Crown Prince Akihito and Crown Princess Michiko were present in both of them.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Earlier it was thought that the Games might not get much media coverage, due to the focus on the Olympic Games, but both radio and television media gave high coverage to the Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Most coverage in the media viewed the new Paralympics highly, and considered its new execution very well-done.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The dedication to those with a variety of disabilities was thought to contribute to overall "international goodwill." This also made the Paralympic organization seem more "humane" since it was thought to be a good way of integrating disabled people into social and work environments.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] British press was notably criticized by the founder of the games, Dr Ludwig Guttmann, for what he considered to be "poor coverage" of the games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] He felt that in comparison to other countries, British press seemed to view the Paralympics not as a sports event, but as standard news.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Yoshisuke Kasai was the chairman of the board of directors.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The board had 3 vice-chairmen, namely T.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] The auditor of the organizing committee was M.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1964-summer-paralympics] Tozawa, and the secretary general was K.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The **1968 Summer Paralympics** (Hebrew: המשחקים הפאראלימפיים בקיץ 1968) were the third Paralympic Games to be held.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Organised under the guidance of the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation (ISMGF), they were known as the **17th International Stoke Mandeville Games** at the time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The games were originally planned to be held alongside the 1968 Summer Olympics in Mexico City, but in 1966, the Mexican government decided against it due to difficulties.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The Israeli government offered to host the games in Tel Aviv, a suggestion that was accepted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The opening ceremony took place in the Hebrew University stadium at the Givat Ram campus in Jerusalem and the games took place in Ramat Gan, Tel Aviv District, at the Israel Sports Center for the Disabled.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The closing ceremony took place in the Tel Aviv Trade Center.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Therefore, these games were the first in Paralympic history to not be held concurrently with the Olympic Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Lawn bowls was included in the program for the first time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] In wheelchair basketball, a women's team event was added, as was a 100 m wheelchair race for men in athletics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The top ten listed NOCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] The host nation, Israel, is highlighted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Twenty-eight delegations took part in the Tel Aviv Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Canada, Denmark, Ethiopia, India, Jamaica, New Zealand, South Korea and Spain took part in the Summer Paralympics for the first time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] Having made its Paralympic Games début four years earlier, South Africa continued to compete at the Paralympics, by sending a delegation to the Tel Aviv Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1968-summer-paralympics] It was, at the time, banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of apartheid, but it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980 Summer Paralympics in Arnhem.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] The **1972 Summer Paralympics** (German: *Paralympische Sommerspiele 1972*), the fourth edition of the Paralympic Games, were held in Heidelberg, West Germany, from 2 to 11 August 1972.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Organised under the guidance of the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation (ISMGF), they were known as the **21st International Stoke Mandeville Games** at the time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] The games ended 15 days before the 1972 Summer Olympics held in Munich, also in West Germany.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] As with previous Paralympics, the 1972 games were intended for wheelchair athletes only.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] However, demonstration events such as goalball and a 100 m sprint for the visually impaired allowed visually impaired competitors to participate for the first time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] The host nation, West Germany, is highlighted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Forty-two delegations took part in the Heidelberg Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Bahamas, Brazil, Czechoslovakia, Egypt, Hong Kong, Hungary, Kenya, Malaysia, Mexico, Peru, Poland, Romania, Uganda and Yugoslavia competed for the first time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Between 1964 and 1976, South Africa was competing at the Paralympics for the third time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Although banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of apartheid, it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980, and West Germany, as host country, did not object to its participation.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] Its invitation to take part in the 1972 Summer Olympics was withdrawn by the International Olympic Committee four days before the opening ceremony, in response to African countries' protests against the Rhodesian government.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1972-summer-paralympics] But as the Paralympics that year were held before the Olympics (and between 1968 and 1984 organised independently ), Rhodesia was able to take part in the 1972 Paralympic Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The **1976 Summer Paralympics** (French: *Jeux paralympiques d'été de 1976*), branded as **Torontolympiad – 1976 Olympiad for the Physically Disabled**, was the fifth Paralympic Games to be held.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] They were hosted by Toronto, Ontario, Canada, from 3 to 11 August 1976, marking the first time a Paralympics was held in the Americas and in Canada.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The games began two days after the close of the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] This was the first time global politics interfered with the Paralympic Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The provincial government at Queen's Park eventually covered the tab.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Two groups, both with the same President - Ludwig Guttmann - were involved in the decision-making: the International Sports Organisation for the Disabled and the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Guttman and Robert Jackson, Chairman of the Organizing Committee, worked to convince the Canadian government to honour their promises of support the teams without money to send their delegations and were largely successful.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Nevertheless, a small number of African countries withdrew to participate in Paralympics, following on from the 1976 Summer Olympics when 25 countries boycotted the Games, and after this situation, those National Olympic Committees were threatened with exclusion from future events.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Later, a series of efforts were made to develop a joint policy with the International Olympic Committee.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Rhodesia was not allowed to participate as the Canadian government refused to grant visas for the Rhodesian Paralympic team to attend the competition.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The opening of the 1976 games was held at Woodbine Race Track in north Etobicoke.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] There was no athletes' village, so competitors were housed at collegial campus of York University (Keele campus), University of Toronto (St.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] George Campus), and the CNIB national headquarters.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Israeli athletes were housed in a fourth secret venue due to the specific and undisclosed security concerns, and fear of a terrorist attack.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Closing ceremonies and the athletics events took place at Centennial Park Stadium.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Centennial Gymnasium and Centennial Park's Olympic Pool were the venues for the swimming events.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The 1976 games marked the first time that there was television coverage of Paralympic events.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Some events were shown live, with daily bulletins shown to viewers in Southern Ontario.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Within the Toronto area, a small consortium of local cable companies (including Trillium Cable and Rogers Cable) carried the games on channel 10 after CTV and Global TV declined to carry them.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] At the 1976 games, amputees and visually impaired athletes competed for the first time; previous editions of the Paralympic Games had included only wheelchair athletes.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Within the sport of athletics, new wheelchair racing distances of 200 m, 400 m, 800 m and 1500 m were added.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Shooting and goalball, both previously demonstration events, were included as official medal sports.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] The host nation, Canada, is highlighted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Forty-one delegations took part in the Toronto Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Burma, Colombia, Ecuador, Greece, Guatemala, Indonesia and Luxembourg made their first appearances.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] South Africa was competing at the Paralympics for the fourth time.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] Although banned from the Olympic Games due to its policy of apartheid, it was not banned from the Paralympics until 1980, and Canada, as host country, did not object to its participation.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-summer-paralympics] These were, however, to be its last Paralympics before the dismantling of apartheid; The Netherlands, as hosts of the 1980 Games, declared South Africa's further participation "undesirable".
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The **1976 Winter Paralympic Games** (Swedish: *Paralympiska vinterspelen 1976*) were the first Winter Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] They were held in Örnsköldsvik, Sweden, from 21 to 28 February 1976.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The disabilities included in this Paralympics were blindness and amputees.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] Sixteen countries took part with 196 athletes.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] There were competitions in Alpine and Nordic skiing for amputee and visually impaired athletes, and a demonstration event in ice sledge racing.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] They were originally known as the **1st Winter Olympic Games for the Disabled**.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The top 9 NPCs by number of gold medals are listed below.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] The host nation (Sweden) is highlighted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] In brackets is the number of athletes per nation.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1976-winter-paralympics] British involvement in these Games was covered in an edition of the Thames Television current affairs series *This Week*.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The **1980 Summer Paralympics** (Dutch: *Paralympische Zomerspelen 1980*), branded as the **Olympics for the Disabled**, were the sixth Summer Paralympic Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] They were held in Arnhem, Netherlands, from 21 to 30 June 1980.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The Soviet Union, hosts of the 1980 Summer Olympics, were invited to host these Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] However, disability sport was not there, and they passed; notoriously, a statement was issued denying the existence of any disabled people in the country (labelled "invalids" by Soviet officials).
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Soviet Paralympic teams were first represented in the 1988 Summer and Winter Games, also the last while the Soviet Union was extant.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The first Paralympics on former Soviet territory would be in 2014.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] There was controversy during the preparation for these Games over the inclusion of a team from South Africa.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] In the Netherlands, public and official opinion was against the inclusion of the South African team and pressure came from a number of sports organisations against the Organising Committee.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The Dutch Parliament was negative as well.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Eventually, the parliament decided against allowing the participation of the South African team.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Although "much of the publicity relating to the South African participation had been negative, it did succeed in bringing the disabled sports movement into the minds of many people who would not have otherwise considered the subject at all.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Dutch organisers also increased visibility through their fundraising ... building a fund that would hold a surplus years after the games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The 1980 Paralympics were the first ever to have mascots: a pair of squirrels, Noggi and Joggi, designed by Necky Oprinsen from Sint-Michielsgestel.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] They were chosen through a design competition by Dutch broadcaster AVRO.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Competitors were divided into four disability categories: amputee, cerebral palsy, visually impaired, and wheelchair.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] It was the first time that cerebral palsy athletes competed in the Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Volleyball was added to the program as a new sport.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Forty-three delegations took part in the Arnhem Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Iceland, Kuwait and Sudan made their first appearances.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] Prior to the Games, the States General (national Parliament) of the Netherlands, as host country, adopted a motion declaring South Africa's participation "undesirable", due to its policy of apartheid.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The 1980 Games thus marked South Africa's first absence from the Summer Paralympics since it had joined the movement in 1964, and it remained absent until 1992.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The Netherlands' decision thus corrected the anomaly whereby South Africa had been banned from the Olympic movement since 1960, while still being authorised to take part in the Paralympic Games.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-summer-paralympics] The host nation, Netherlands, is highlighted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] The **1980 Winter Paralympic Games** (Norwegian: *Paralympiske vinterleker 1980*; Nynorsk: *Paralympiske vinterleikane 1980*), the second Winter Paralympics, were held from 1 to 7 February 1980 in Geilo, Norway.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] Eighteen countries took part with 299 athletes.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] A demonstration event was held in sledge downhill racing.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] All classes of athletes with locomotor disabilities were able to participate.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] Organized by the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation (ISMGF) and the International Sports Federation of the Disabled (ISOD).
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] Originally known as the **2nd Olympic Winter Games for Disabled**.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] The host nation (Norway) is highlighted.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] Eighteen nations participated in the 1980 Winter Paralympics.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] Australia, Denmark, Italy and New Zealand made their debut appearances.
[src:1980-winter-paralympics/1980-winter-paralympics] Belgium and Poland did not send any athletes.
